GroundWater

Rozerin Yıldız Peteksu Karpuz

04 06 2022

  • Project Description

  • Description of problem

  • Groundwater quality monitoring is carried out under the State Environmental Monitoring coordinated by the Chief Inspector of Environmental Protection. The purpose of groundwater quality monitoring is to provide information on the chemical status of groundwater, track its changes and signal threats on a national scale, for the purposes of managing groundwater resources and assessing the effectiveness of protective measures taken.

  • Dataset

  • Dataset : https://www.kaggle.com/datasets/krystianadammolenda/poland-2020

  • Monitoring of groundwater quality dataset.

  • 55 Column - 769 Row

  • Columns

  • ID : Ordinal number of each of the saved measurements

  • UE_ID_MEASURING_POINT : UE identifier of the measuring point

  • X_PL1992 : Coordinate ‘x’ according to the PL-1992 National Geodetic Coordinate System

  • Y_PL1992 : Coordinate ‘y’ according to the PL-1992 National Geodetic Coordinate System

  • VOIVODESHIP : Name of the voivodeship in English (in Polish in brackets)

  • DISTRICT : Name of the poviat (district) in Polish

  • COMMUNITY : Name of the commune in Polish

  • CITY : The name of the city in Polish

  • BASIN_NAME : River basin name

  • CAT_LAND : Land use category

  • DATE_SAMPLING : Date of sampling

  • CONDUCT_FIELD : Specific electrolytic conductivity at 20 °C - field value [µS/cm]

  • PH_FIELD : pH value - field value [-]

  • TEMP_FIELD : Temperature - field value [°C]

  • O2_DISSOL_FIELD : Dissolved oxygen - field value [mgO₂/l]

  • CONDUCT_LAB : Specific electrolytic conductivity at 20 °C - laboratory value [µS/cm]

  • PH_LAB : pH value - laboratory value [-]

  • CON_C : Organic carbon concentration [mgC/l]

  • CON_NH4+ : Ammonium ions concentration [mgNH₄⁺/l]

  • CON_Sb : Antimony concentration [mgSb/l]

  • CON_As : Arsenic concentration [mgAs/l]

  • CON_NO3- : Nitrate(V) ions concentration [mgNO₃⁻/l]

  • CON_NO2- : Nitrate(III) ions concentration [mgNO₂⁻/l]

  • CON_Ba : Barium concentration [mgBa/l]

  • CON_Be : Beryllium concentration [mgBe/l]

  • CON_B : Boron concentration [mgB/l]

  • CON_Cl- : Chloride ions concentration [mgCl⁻/l]

  • CON_Cr : Chromium concentration [mgCr/l]

  • CON_CN- : Cyanide ions concentration [mgCN⁻/l]

  • CON_Sn : Tin concentration [mgSn/l]

  • CON_Zn : Zinc concentration [mgZn/l]

  • CON_F- : Fluoride ions concentration [mgF⁻/l]

  • CON_PO43- : Phosphate(V) ion concentration [mgPO₄³⁻/l]

  • CON_Al : Aluminum concentration [mgAl/l]

  • CON_Cd : Cadmium concentration [mgCd/l]

  • CON_Co : Cobalt concentration [mgCo/l]

  • CON_Mg : Magnesium concentration [mgMg/l]

  • CON_Mn : Manganese concentration [mgMn/l]

  • CON_Cu : Copper concentration [mgCu/l]

  • CON_Mo : Molybdenum concentration [mgMo/l]

  • CON_Ni : Nickel concentration [mgNi/l]

  • CON_Pb : Lead concentration [mgPb/l]

  • CON_K : Potassium concentration [mgK/l]

  • CON_Hg : Mercury concentration [mgHg/l]

  • CON_Se : Selenium concentration [mgSe/l]

  • CON_SO42 : Sulfate(VI) ions concentration [mgSO₄ ²⁻/l]

  • CON_Na : Sodium concentration [mgNa/l]

  • CON_Ag : Silver concentration [mgAg/l]

  • CON_Tl : Thallium concentration [mgTl/l]

  • CON_Tl : Titanium concentration [mgTi/l]

  • CON_U : Uranium concentration [mgU/l]

  • CON_v : Vanadium concentration [mgV/l]

  • CON_Ca : Calcium concentration [mgCa/l]

  • CON_HCO3 : Bicarbonate ions concentration [mgHCO⁻/l]

  • CON_Fe : Iron concentration [mgFe/l]

  • Categorical data columns : BASIN_NAME, CITY, UE_ID_MEASURING_POINT, VOIVODESHIP, DISTRICT, COMMUNITY, CAT_LAND

  • Ordinal data columns : DATE_SAMPLING

  • Quantitative data columns: The rest of the other columns.

-CENTRAL LIMIT THEOREM - The central limit theorem states that the sampling distribution of a sample mean is approximately normal if the sample size is large enough, even if the population distribution is not normal.

  • The central limit theorem also states that the sampling distribution will have the following properties:

    1. The mean of the sampling distribution will be equal to the mean of the population distribution:

  • x = μ

    1. The standard deviation of the sampling distribution will be equal to the standard deviation of the population distribution divided by the sample size:

  • s = σ / n

samplingfunc<-function(size){
  tempfield <- dataset$TEMP_FIELD

  sample <- sample(tempfield, size)

  return(sample)
}
hist(col='orange',samplingfunc(30) , main = 'n=30')

hist(col='green', samplingfunc(50), main = 'n=50')

hist(col ='light blue', samplingfunc(100), main = 'n=100')

- To increase normality, we randomly created a sampling function. It takes a size parameter and returns the sample. Thus, since the samples we created were in random and different sizes, they gave results closer to normal and reflected on the histograms.

conductfield <- dataset$CONDUCT_FIELD
hist(col ='light green', conductfield, border = 'purple')

shapiro.test(conductfield)
## 
##  Shapiro-Wilk normality test
## 
## data:  conductfield
## W = 0.82218, p-value < 2.2e-16
  • The column we chose according to the Shapiro result is actually close to normal. However, as can be seen in the histogram, it is formed in a right skewed manner. We will put this column into a more normal distribution with the help of boxcox and logarithmic transformation.
library(MASS)
## 
## Attaching package: 'MASS'
## The following object is masked from 'package:dplyr':
## 
##     select
boxcox(lm(conductfield ~ 1))

- The center dashed vertical line represents the estimated parameter λλ and the others the 95% confidence interval of the estimation.

  • As the plot shows that the 0 is inside the confidence interval of the optimal λand as the estimation of the parameter is really close to 0, the best option is to apply the logarithmic transformation of the data
# Transformed data
new_conductfield <- log(conductfield)

# Histogram
hist(col ='light pink',new_conductfield)

- Now the data looks more like following a normal distribution, we also performed,a statistical test to check it, as the Shapiro-Wilk test:

shapiro.test(new_conductfield)
## 
##  Shapiro-Wilk normality test
## 
## data:  new_conductfield
## W = 0.97801, p-value = 2.558e-09
  • p-value < 0.05, so we reject the null hypothesis and our new column is more normal than before.

-SINGLE T-TEST

  • Aim : It is used to determine whether an unknown population mean is different from a specific value.
  • We chose Wilcoxon rank-sum test, because a one-sample Wilcoxon test is used to test whether the median of a population, from which a sample is drawn, is statistically different from a hypothesised value.
  • One sample hypothesis for mean of temperature for basin name is Odra and testing it with 95% confidence interval. And significant level is 0.05.
  • H0: μ = 10 (The mean of temperature field value is equal to 10.)
  • H1: μ != 10 (The mean of temperature field value is not equal to 10.)
  • First of all, we will apply Shapiro-Wilk normality test to check normality of temperature for Basins.
shapiro.test(dataset$TEMP_FIELD)
## 
##  Shapiro-Wilk normality test
## 
## data:  dataset$TEMP_FIELD
## W = 0.88264, p-value < 2.2e-16
  • The p-value is not greater than 0.05, so data is not normally distributed and the below plot indicates that.
qqnorm(col='dark blue',dataset$TEMP_FIELD, ylab = "Temperature field value of Odra Basin")
qqline(col='red',dataset$TEMP_FIELD)

library(ggplot2)
skewness(dataset$TEMP_FIELD, na.rm = TRUE)
## [1] 1.753918
  • Since the output value is >0, it is skewed to the right (asymmetrical)
wilcox.test(dataset$TEMP_FIELD, mu = 10, conf.int = TRUE, conf.level = 0.95)
## 
##  Wilcoxon signed rank test with continuity correction
## 
## data:  dataset$TEMP_FIELD
## V = 252549, p-value < 2.2e-16
## alternative hypothesis: true location is not equal to 10
## 95 percent confidence interval:
##  10.75002 10.90002
## sample estimates:
## (pseudo)median 
##       10.84996
  • Conclusion : As seen above p-value is less than 0.05 so there is sufficient evidence that the mean number of temperature field value is not equal to 10. We reject the null hypothesis and the confidence interval is between 10.85 and 11.05 with 95% confidence which does not contain the hypothesized mean(10).

-Possible Errors: - Type1 Error -> Mean = 10 but we rejected the null hypothesis. - Type2 Error -> Mean != 10 but we did not reject the null hypothesis.

-TWO SAMPLE TEST

  • Are there significant difference between mean of temperature field value for basin name is Odra and Other basin ?

  • Aim : The paired samples t-test is used to compare the means between two related groups of samples. Our groups are basin name and temperature field value.

  • Hypothesis :

  • H0: μ1 = μ2 (Mean of basins is equal to mean of temperatue field values.)

  • H1: μ1 != μ2 (Mean of basins is not equal to mean of temperatue field values.)

tempdata = read.csv("C:\\Users\\petek\\Desktop\\Groundwater_parameters.csv")

-Fisher’s exact test - Aim: Fisher’s exact test is a non-parametric method for comparing the proportion of categories in two different independent groups (categorical [nominal] variables) in a contingency table. We choose Basin and Categorical Land as categorical data. - Hypothesis : - H0 = Basin and category land are independent. - H1 = Basin and category land are dependent.

tempdata2 = read.csv("C:\\Users\\petek\\Desktop\\Groundwater_parameters.csv")
tempdata2$BASIN_NAME[tempdata2$BASIN_NAME!="Odra basin"]<-"Other basin"
tempdata2$CAT_LAND[tempdata2$CAT_LAND!="04. Rural buildings"]<-"Other catland"

dataforfisher <- tempdata2[, c(9, 10)]
colnames(dataforfisher) <- c("Basin", "catland")

BasinName <- dataforfisher$Basin
Catland <- dataforfisher$catland

#In order to apply the Fisher Exact Test correctly, we visualized the two categorical variables we used in a contingency table.
table <- table(BasinName,Catland)
table
##              Catland
## BasinName     04. Rural buildings Other catland
##   Odra basin                  113           274
##   Other basin                 142           240
fisher.test(table, conf.int = 0.95)
## 
##  Fisher's Exact Test for Count Data
## 
## data:  table
## p-value = 0.02152
## alternative hypothesis: true odds ratio is not equal to 1
## 95 percent confidence interval:
##  0.5094065 0.9532103
## sample estimates:
## odds ratio 
##  0.6973692

  • Conclusion : Since, the p-value < 0.05, we reject the null hypothesis, so Basin and category land are dependent.

  • Odds Ratio :

  • The odds ratio is a measure of how far from independence the 2x2 table is. the exposed group has half, or 50%, of the odds of developing disease as the unexposed group. Since odd ratio value is 0.69, it is less than 1. So independent degree is less than dependent degree.

  • ANOVA

  • Aim: It is used to help to understand how different groups respond, with a null hypothesis for the test that the means of the different groups are equal. If there is a statistically significant result, then it means that the two populations are unequal (or different).

  • Are there significant difference between mean of temperature field values for different basins?

  • Hypothesis:

  • H0: μ1=μ2=μ3 (There is a significant difference between mean of temperature field values for different basins.)

  • H1: At least one differs.

  • MULTIPLE LINEAR REGRESSION

  • H0:βJ=0 (there is no (linear) relationship between the three variables)

  • H1:βJ≠0 (there is a (linear) relationship between the three variables)
